<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As world leaders at the seven-nation
economic debated the world's future, their spouses toured this
historic city for a glimpse of <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>' past.
   First Lady <PERSON>Barbara Bush</PERSON> led the summit wives on a 20-minute tour
of <LOCATION>Mission San Jose</LOCATION>, one of five old Spanish missions still
standing in <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION>. The fort-like stone mission was built in
<DATE>1720</DATE> by a Franciscan priest for teaching Christianity and European
culture to the Indians.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Bush</PERSON>'s guests included <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Danielle Mitterrand</PERSON>,
<LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Mila Mulroney</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Livia Andreotti</PERSON> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Sachiyo
Kaifu</PERSON>.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Denis Thatcher</PERSON>, the only male summit spouse, skipped
the tour.
   <PERSON>Hannelore Kohl</PERSON>, wife of West German Chancellor <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON>, and
<PERSON>Marie Delors</PERSON>, wife of <ORGANIZATION>European Commission</ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON>Jacques Delors</PERSON>,
did not accompany their husbands to <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>.
   After touring the mission, the women went to a private luncheon
at the home Joci and <PERSON>Joe Straus, Jr.</PERSON>, longtime friends of the
Bushes, followed by a tour of the Alamo and the renovated Majestic
Theater.
   At one time, <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION> was a contender as the economic summit
site, but it lost out to <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>'s adopted hometown.
   The Alamo is the site of the historic <DATE>1836</DATE> battle between the
Mexican army and men led by Col. <PERSON>William Travis</PERSON> who were fighting
for <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>' independence from <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>.
   Mexican Gen. <PERSON>Santa Anna</PERSON>'s troops greatly outnumbered the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>'s
defenders, who were besieged for 14 days before the Mexicans
attacked. All 189 of <PERSON>Travis</PERSON>' men were killed.
   The incident gave birth to the battle cry, ``Remember the
Alamo!'' used by other Texans who fought for freedom.
   After visiting <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION>, the spouses were returning to
<LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, where they planned to tour the <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> Medical Center on
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the final day of the summit.
   On <DATE>Monday</DATE>, the spouses were guests of <LOCATION>Betty</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Hugh Liedtkes</PERSON>,
close friends of the Bushes, for a dinner in the upscale Memorial
neighborhood in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>.
   Liedtke is a wealthy oil man who knew <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> when the president
was in the oil business in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> before entering politics.
   The menu included quail, gazpacho soup, shrimp creole remoulade,
poached snapper and asparagus. Dessert was called <ORGANIZATION>Strawberries
Summit</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> and <PERSON>Liedtke</PERSON> met years ago in <LOCATION>West Texas</LOCATION> while both were in
the oil business, and they helped form <ORGANIZATION>Zapata Petroleum</ORGANIZATION>.
Eventually, the company's investors spilt, although <PERSON>Liedtke</PERSON> and
<PERSON>Bush</PERSON> remained friends.
   Liedtke is the former chief of Houston-based <ORGANIZATION>Pennzoil Co.</ORGANIZATION>, the
oil company that won an <MONEY>$10.3 billion</MONEY> judgment in <DATE>1985</DATE> from <ORGANIZATION>Texaco
Inc.</ORGANIZATION> over <ORGANIZATION>Texaco</ORGANIZATION>'s takeover of <ORGANIZATION>Getty Oil Co</ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION>Pennzoil</ORGANIZATION> later settled
for <MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY>.
   Liedtke is still chairman of <ORGANIZATION>Pennzoil</ORGANIZATION>'s board.
