<HEAD>Sightseeing, Socializing On Summit Spouses Schedule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the summit leaders focus on global issues,
their spouses have a full schedule of sightseeing and socializing,
starting with a private dinner at friends of President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>'s
<DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>.
   The seven leaders of the industrialized world planned a working
dinner <DATE>Monday</DATE> at <ORGANIZATION>Bayou Bend</ORGANIZATION>, a mansion-turned-museum, while they
spouses were guests of <LOCATION>Betty</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Hugh Liedtkes</PERSON>.
   The Liedtkes, close friends of both <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON>Barbara</PERSON>,
invited the spouses to their home for dinner in the upscale
Memorial neighborhood. Liedtke is a wealthy oil man who knew <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>
when the president was in the oil business in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> before entering
politics.
   On <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, the spouses planned to fly to <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION> to tour
the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>Mission San Jose</LOCATION> and the renovated Majestic Theatre.
<LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION> also was in the running to host the economic summit,
but the city lost out to <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>'s adopted hometown. .
   The Alamo is the site of the historic <DATE>1836</DATE> battle between the
Mexican army and a group of men led by Col. <PERSON>William Travis</PERSON> who were
fighting for <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>' independence from <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>.
   Mexican Gen. <PERSON>Santa Anna</PERSON>'s troops greatly outnumbered the Alamo
forces, although historical records do not provide an exact number.
The Mexican soldiers laid siege on the Alamo for 14 days before
attacking.
   All of <PERSON>Travis</PERSON>' men _ 189 _ were killed, and the tragic fight
gave birth to the battle cry, ``Remember the Alamo!'' for other
Texans fighting for freedom.
   After visiting <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION>, the spouses were to return to
<LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>. They also planned to tour the <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> Medical Center on
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the final day of the summit.
   Besides <PERSON>Mrs. Bush</PERSON>, the spouses include <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Danielle
Mitterrand</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Mila Mulroney</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Livia Andreotti</PERSON>,
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Sachiyo Kaifu</PERSON> and <LOCATION>England</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Denis Thatcher</PERSON>, the only male
spouse.
   <PERSON>Hannelore Kohl</PERSON>, wife of West German Chancellor <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON>, and
<PERSON>Marie Delors</PERSON>, wife of <ORGANIZATION>European Commission</ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON>Jacques Delors</PERSON>
did not accompany their husbands to <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>.
   The wives of several other local leaders also planned to attend
<DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>'s dinner at the <PERSON>Liedtke</PERSON> home. The menu included quail,
gazpacho soup, shrimp creole remoulade, poached snapper and
asparagus. Dessert was called strawberries summit.
   After dinner, the group was to be entertained by a string trio
and a singing duo. The trio's members are all teen-agers.
   <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> and <PERSON>Liedtke</PERSON> met years ago in <LOCATION>West Texas</LOCATION> while both were in
the oil business, and they helped form <ORGANIZATION>Zapata Petroleum</ORGANIZATION>.
Eventually, the company's investors spilt, although <PERSON>Liedtke</PERSON> and
<PERSON>Bush</PERSON> remained friends.
   Liedtke is the former chief of Houston-based <ORGANIZATION>Pennzoil Co.</ORGANIZATION>, the
oil company that won an <MONEY>$10.3 billion</MONEY> judgment in <DATE>1985</DATE> from <ORGANIZATION>Texaco
Inc.</ORGANIZATION> over <ORGANIZATION>Texaco</ORGANIZATION>'s takeover of <ORGANIZATION>Getty Oil Co</ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION>Pennzoil</ORGANIZATION> later settled
for <MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY>.
   Liedtke is still chairman of <ORGANIZATION>Pennzoil</ORGANIZATION>'s board.
</TEXT>
