<SECOND>AM-Alamo Movie, Adv 29,1097</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Advance for Mon AMs, Feb 29, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: `Kieth' is cq in 6th graf</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE COCHRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At age 65, native <PERSON>Texan George A.
McAlister</PERSON> is a big, friendly, drawling former coach, educator and
inventor turned businessman, rancher, historian, author and dreamer.
   His dream was to make a film based on the battle of the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>.
That dream is coming true.
   With blazing cannons and bloody sabres, the heroes of the Alamo
relive on a giant new screen this week the fateful 13-day siege
that inspired <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> to win its independence from <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION> in <DATE>1836</DATE>. A
black-tie premiere of the docudrama is set for <DATE>Saturday</DATE>.
   Entitled ``Alamo ... The Price of Freedom,'' the 45-minute film
is an account of the battle based largely on the research and books
of <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON>, and it has stirred some controversy.
   Academy Award-winning filmmaker <PERSON>Kieth Merrill</PERSON> directed the
movie, part of a <MONEY>$7.2 million</MONEY> project that includes a new IMAX
theater with its 84{-foot wide, six-story high screen. The 426-seat
theater is housed in the new <ORGANIZATION>Rivercenter Mall</ORGANIZATION>, which overlooks the
Alamo grounds.
   The IMAX system is designed to give viewers visually stunning
images as well as a sense of participation in the on-screen
activity.
   ``The Price of Freedom'' was filmed <DATE>last summer</DATE> at <LOCATION>Alamo Village</LOCATION>
near <LOCATION>Brackettville</LOCATION>, where <PERSON>John Wayne</PERSON> built the set for his epic
<DATE>1960</DATE> film, ``The Alamo.''
   <DATE>Saturday</DATE>'s premiere benefits the research library operated by
the Daughters of the Republic of <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and includes a reception and
dinner-dance and remarks by <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION> billionaire <PERSON>Nelson Bunker Hunt</PERSON>.
   Gov. <PERSON>Bill Clements</PERSON> will be on hand the next day for formal
dedication ceremonies, which coincide with the 152nd anniversary of
the fall of the Alamo to Mexican Gen. <LOCATION>Santa Anna</LOCATION>.
   ``There are two great symbols of freedom in <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON>
said. ``First is the Statue of Liberty. But it is just that _ a
symbol of freedom. Then there is this old stone mission, the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>,
a shrine to the price of freedom.
   ``And there is a difference between a symbol of freedom and a
price of freedom.''
   A veteran of World War II and the Korean conflict, <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON>
pointed out gently that a lot of people are willing to live for a
cause but only a very few are willing to die for one.
   ``The defenders of the Alamo were willing to die for freedom,''
he said. ``And more than 3 million people from all over the world
came to the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> <DATE>last year</DATE> to pay homage to those 189 brave men
who gave their lives that <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> might be free.''
   McAlister once stood outside the Alamo for days asking visitors
if they would pay to see an authentic movie of the historic battle
and if they were familiar with IMAX theaters.
   He liked the answers. And the premiere this <DATE>weekend</DATE> showcases
the results of that private poll.
   While stressing the importance of authenticity, <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON> points
out quickly that much of what occurred at the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> is subject to
speculation and individual interpretation.
   ``There are no chronicles of the Alamo and what happened
there,'' he said.
   Still, <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON> spent 12 years researching his books. His
travels took him to <LOCATION>Goliad</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>San Jacinto</LOCATION>, Washington-on-the-Brazos
and other battle sites and to <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Tennessee</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION>
and <LOCATION>Alabama</LOCATION> to visit the hometowns of the most famous defenders of
the Alamo: Col. <PERSON>William B. Travis</PERSON>, <PERSON>Jim Bowie</PERSON>, <PERSON>Davy Crockett</PERSON> and
<PERSON>James Bonham</PERSON>.
   McAlister also describes the Alamo contribution of the Tejanos,
the nine Mexicans who supported the <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> cause.
   He and his colleagues say they have made their movie as
historically accurate as possible without sacrificing dramatic and
entertainment value.
   ``If we were going to make a movie for several generations, I
did not want it to be fiction,'' <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON> said.
   The movie has no stars but uses 450 members of war-enactment
societies across the country who are dedicated to historical
accuracy, costume and customs.
   McAlister was surprised and dismayed when <LOCATION>San Antonio City</LOCATION>
Councilman <PERSON>Walter Martinez</PERSON> and a group of residents accused the
producers of distorting historical facts.
   After viewing a rough cut of the movie, <PERSON>Martinez</PERSON> complained that
the film demeaned Hispanics by making them look like bad guys, and
presented a list of objections to <ORGANIZATION>Texas Cavalcade Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, the
production group headed by <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Kathy Pena-Sosa</PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION>Texas Cavalcade</ORGANIZATION>, said some
objectionable scenes were deleted in the final editing from 73
minutes to 45 minutes, but professed to be puzzled by the criticism.
   ``In a community that's <PERCENT>54 percent</PERCENT> Hispanic,'' she said, ``we're
not going to make a movie that's offensive to Hispanics.''
   Born and raised in <LOCATION>East Texas</LOCATION>, <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON> got his first exposure
to <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> history in a two-room, two-teacher schoolhouse in a tiny
hamlet near <ORGANIZATION>Commerce</ORGANIZATION>.
   He interrupted his collegiate studies at <ORGANIZATION>East Texas State</ORGANIZATION> in
<DATE>1942</DATE> to enlist in the Marines, but returned after the war to get a
master's degree in math. His minor was history.
   During an academic career that was interrupted when he was
recalled to active duty in <LOCATION>Korea</LOCATION> in <DATE>1950</DATE>, <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON> was a dean at
<ORGANIZATION>Howard County Junior College in Big Spring</ORGANIZATION>, as well as chairman of
the math department, coach of the track team and an amateur
inventor.
   In <DATE>1955</DATE>, with <MONEY>$150</MONEY>, he founded a company called <ORGANIZATION>GAMCO</ORGANIZATION> to create
and build teaching aids for math students, including a classroom
computer and an electronic teaching machine. The sale of <ORGANIZATION>GAMCO</ORGANIZATION> in
<DATE>1966</DATE> made him a millionaire.
   It also freed him to pursue his ranching and writing interests
and to devote more time to historical research.
   His first novel, ``Nothing is Forever,'' was based on the early
life of Travis. That book evolved into a second novel, ``A Time to
Love ... A Time to Die.''
   This led in turn to ``Alamo ... The Price of Freedom,'' a
non-fiction book which <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON> describes as ``history as I view
it and my personal research reveals it.''
   For <PERSON>McAlister</PERSON>, ``The Price of Freedom'' is more than a movie or
a business venture.
   Said he: ``I would like to leave a legacy on the screen that
retells the story of this sacrifice for freedom ... that
demonstrates to a new generation that freedom isn't free ... that
liberty rests finally on those willing to die for it.''
</TEXT>
