<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Smile When You Say
   `Lost Cause,' Podner
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<RE>
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
TEXAS (TX)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Your June 10 article calling Alamo, Texas, the "famous
namesake of a lost cause" must have raised the hair on the
nape of every Texan and student of Texas history. Of course,
you were referring to the Battle of the Alamo, which took
place in San Antonio in March 1836. But as to the "lost
cause," I haven't a clue as to what you were talking about.
The Texas Revolution, of which the siege of the Alamo was an
integral part, was far from a lost cause.
   The delay inflicted upon the Mexican army by the tenacious
defenders of the Alamo gave Sam Houston time to gather his
ragtag Texan irregulars and make a stand a month later at the
Battle of San Jacinto, near what is now Houston. There they
routed Santa Anna's army and won independence for the
Republic of Texas.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   If the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> had been part of a lost cause, there would
not only be no <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>, but probably no <LOCATION>Wyoming</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New Mexico</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Colorado</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Utah</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Nevada</LOCATION> or <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, since these
states came into being as a direct result of the <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>
Revolution and the subsequent <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and Mexican <DATE>War nine years
later</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Jerry W. Grisham
   Houston</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>
</TEXT>
