<HEAD>Austin Urged to Rename Bowie High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hispanic and black leaders are urging
Austin school officials to name a new high school after someone
other than <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> hero <PERSON>James Bowie</PERSON>, arguing that <PERSON>Bowie</PERSON> was a slave
trader.
   <PERSON>Gary Bledsoe</PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION>NAACP</ORGANIZATION>'s Austin chapter, said
<PERSON>Bowie</PERSON> isn't the kind of person whose name should be on a school.
   ``The plain and simple truth, according to some of the most
noted <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> historians ... is that <PERSON>Jim Bowie</PERSON> smuggled slaves into
<LOCATION>North America</LOCATION>, sold them at vastly inflated prices, owned then,
sold fictitious land grants for <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> land, fraudulently sold land
owned by his in-laws and committed many other heinous and nefarious
acts,'' <PERSON>Bledsoe</PERSON> said.
   Black and Hispanic leaders have suggested naming the school
after a Hispanic. No Austin high school has a Hispanic namesake.
   The Daughters of the Republic of <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and 420 other people
recommended that the school be named for <ORGANIZATION>Bowie</ORGANIZATION>. In a <DATE>March</DATE> vote,
the <ORGANIZATION>Austin Independent School District Board of Trustees</ORGANIZATION> approved
<PERSON>Bowie</PERSON>'s name for the school with two board members dissenting. For
the matter to be reheard, a board member who voted in favor of
<LOCATION>Bowie</LOCATION>'s name must move for reconsideration. No such motion was made
at the panel's latest meeting <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   A <LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION> native, <PERSON>Bowie</PERSON> was an adventurer who by age 18 had
earned a reputation for riding alligators and wrestling bears. In
<DATE>1828</DATE>, he moved to <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and settled in <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION>. After first
sharing command at the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> with <PERSON>William B. Travis</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Bowie</ORGANIZATION> fell ill
and died on <DATE>March 6, 1836</DATE>, when Mexican soldiers captured the
mission. A county and a city in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> are named for him.
   The <ORGANIZATION>National Association</ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION>Advancement of Colored People</ORGANIZATION>
and others sent a letter complaining of the name choice to the
school board <DATE>April 11</DATE>.
</TEXT>
