<HEAD>Group Scraps Plans to Buy `Bowie' Knife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A <MONEY>$3.5 million</MONEY> offer for a knife believed to have
belonged to <PERSON>James Bowie</PERSON> during the battle of the Alamo was
withdrawn because the dagger's owner refused to have it tested for
authenticity.
   Spirit of the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>, a non-profit fund-raising group, dropped
the offer, president <PERSON>John Stokes</PERSON> said <DATE>Saturday</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Bartley Dean Moore</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Riverside</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, said family lore has it
that a young Mexican soldier found the knife after the mission fell
in <DATE>1836</DATE>. In <DATE>1890</DATE>, the soldier gave the knife to <PERSON>Moore</PERSON>'s grandfather
in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> to settle a <MONEY>$5</MONEY> debt, the story goes.
   Museum curators and other experts discounted the claim.
   The fund-raising group, formed last year, had agreed to pay <MONEY>$3.5
million</MONEY> if the knife proved genuine, but wanted tests to determine
its age and metal content.
   All 187 American defenders, including <PERSON>Bowie</PERSON> and <PERSON>Davy Crockett</PERSON>,
were killed in the 13-day siege of the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>. Legend credits <PERSON>Bowie</PERSON>
with inventing what is now known as the bowie knife.
</TEXT>
