<HEAD>Workers Find Graffiti Possibly Left By Alamo Defender</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> discovered graffiti that
may have been left by an Alamo defender in <DATE>1836</DATE> on a door of the
mission.
   ``We found original mission plaster,'' <PERSON>Alamo Curator Steve Beck</PERSON>
said. ``There is graffiti in which the dates <DATE>1894</DATE> and <DATE>1897</DATE> are
written in pencil, and the name <PERSON>Mills</PERSON> is inscribed into the surface.
The name is about 4 inches long and 1{ inches tall.''
   The name may have been carved by <PERSON>William Mills</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Tennessee</LOCATION>, who
was among the 189 men known to have died <DATE>March 6, 1836</DATE>, defending
the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> in the struggle for <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> independence.
   ``We don't have any solid proof it was <PERSON>William Mills</PERSON>, but it's a
good possibility,'' <PERSON>Beck</PERSON> said.
   Beck and stone mason <PERSON>Baltazar Espinosa</PERSON> discovered the graffiti as
they worked on the north side of the <ORGANIZATION>Shrine of Texas Liberty</ORGANIZATION> as part
of an ongoing preservation project. The door dates to the early
<DATE>1700s</DATE>, <PERSON>Beck</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
