<HL> So Does This Mean That Texas Remains a Territory of Mexico? </HL>
<AUTHOR> Paul Duke Jr. (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices slide. 
Real estate goes bust. 
Banks collapse. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Dallas Cowboys</ORGANIZATION> notch their first losing season in two decades. 

   Texans have seen plenty of woes in recent years. 
Now, to top it all off, even the value of their printed paper is plunging. 
And not just any paper, but <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>'s proudest heritage, including certain copies of its own <DATE>1836</DATE> Declaration of Independence from <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, which sold for up to <MONEY>$30,000</MONEY>. 

   A number of them have turned out to be phonies. 
Someone -- no one knows who -- has been "diddling around with the stuff of <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> history," says an angry <PERSON>Don Carleton</PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION>Barker Texas History Center</ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION>University of Texas</ORGANIZATION>. 

   And they've been doing so for the past 15 years, according to Austin-based publisher and rare-book dealer <PERSON>W. Thomas Taylor</PERSON>, who alerted <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> booksellers to the problem earlier this month. 
<PERSON>Mr. Taylor</PERSON> himself unwittingly sold several of the phony documents. 

   The duped also include such patriotic <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> bigwigs as Gov. <PERSON>William Clements</PERSON>, as well as numerous libraries and universities, including the <ORGANIZATION>Barker Center</ORGANIZATION>. 
It owns a fake copy of a particularly sacred <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> text, Col. <PERSON>William Barrett Travis</PERSON>'s "Victory or Death" letter, penned just as the Mexican forces closed in on the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>. 

   All of the forgeries purport to be general-distribution circulars printed in the <DATE>1830s</DATE> and <DATE>'40s</DATE>, during the Republic of <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> era. 
But the typefaces used, says <PERSON>Mr. Taylor</PERSON>, weren't invented until decades later. 
Aside from that big gaffe, the fastidious forgers dotted some i's that went undotted in the originals. 
<PERSON>Mr. Taylor</PERSON> figures a total of about 100 false documents are in circulation, and embarassed booksellers around the state are apologetically returning their customers' money. 

   But not all <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> tycoons were taken in. 
A while back, <PERSON>H. Ross Perot</PERSON> was offered a Travis circular. 
Experts at <ORGANIZATION>Yale University</ORGANIZATION>, which has a verified Travis letter, were skeptical, and <PERSON>Mr. Perot</PERSON> passed. 

   Still, that hasn't stopped others from offering him a supposed original <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Declaration of Independence and the sword General <PERSON>Cornwallis</PERSON> surrendered to <LOCATION>George Washington</LOCATION>. 
Says <PERSON>Mr. Perot</PERSON>: "There are days when I think people must believe I'm the biggest patsy around." 

</TEXT>
