<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEBURG, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Davy Crockett</PERSON> is more than the ``king
of the wild frontier'' to his descendants, who are meeting at a
state park that bears his name.
   ``<PERSON>David</PERSON> was quite a man in his time,'' said <PERSON>Joy Bland</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Tenn.</LOCATION>, a great-great-great-great-granddaughter of the <LOCATION>Tennessee</LOCATION>
pioneer. ``We think he made quite a contribution to our state in
many ways.''
   More than 100 people who have traced their roots to <PERSON>Crockett</PERSON>
began gathering at <ORGANIZATION>David Crockett State Park</ORGANIZATION> near here <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
The reunion coincides with <PERSON>David Crockett Days</PERSON>, an annual festival.
   ``We want to keep the knowledge of him alive,'' <PERSON>Ms. Bland</PERSON> said.
``I learn something different every reunion.''
   To be a full member of the four-year-old Descendants of <PERSON>David
Crockett</PERSON> organization, people must trace their lineage to one of
<PERSON>Crockett</PERSON>'s six children, two stepchildren or two wives. Those who
are simply interested in <LOCATION>Crockett</LOCATION> can join as associate members.
   The man who historians say called himself <PERSON>David</PERSON>, not <ORGANIZATION>Davy</ORGANIZATION>,
<PERSON>Crockett</PERSON> was born in <LOCATION>northeast Tennessee</LOCATION> on <DATE>Aug. 17, 1786</DATE>. He
represented the region as a state lawmaker and then was a
congressman in 1827-31 and 1833-35. He died in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> defending the
<LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> in <DATE>1836</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Ms. Bland</PERSON> said <PERSON>Crockett</PERSON>'s record of public service often becomes
lost in the folklore surrounding him, but the frontiersman is
partly to blame.
   ``He liked to hunt, and he liked to talk about it,'' <PERSON>Ms. Bland</PERSON>
said. ``He only shot big bears.''
   Walt Disney Studios recently announced plans for a new
television series about <PERSON>Crockett</PERSON>. In the <DATE>'50s</DATE>, the orignal Disney
series starring <PERSON>Fess Parker</PERSON> had every kid in <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> wanting to
dress in coonskin.
   ``I really hope they will try to teach the public something
about the man that he was,'' said <PERSON>Ms. Bland</PERSON>. ``If children have
heroes today, it ought to be someone like him.''
</TEXT>
