<HEAD>Gephardt Says He's Best Candidate on Energy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. <PERSON>Richard Gephardt</PERSON> emphasized his
support for an oil-import fee on <DATE>Monday</DATE>, one day before four
oil-producing states vote on Super <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, then went to the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>
to call himself the Democratic candidate for economic independence.
   ``We're standing today in front of the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>, a place where
there was a fight for independence,'' <PERSON>Gephardt</PERSON> said. ``This
election in <DATE>1988</DATE> is a fight again for the independence of <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>,
the fight for us to regain control of our economic destiny.''
   Gephardt spoke to about 400 supporters and tourists in this
city, generally considered a stronghold for <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION> Gov.
<PERSON>Michael Dukakis</PERSON>, after speaking at a struggling <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION> plant that
makes equipment for the oil industry.
   <PERSON>Dukakis</PERSON> was at the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> <DATE>Sunday</DATE>. Many of the Democrats here are
Hispanic, and <PERSON>Dukakis</PERSON> spoke to them in fluent Spanish.
   But Rep. <PERSON>Albert Bustamante</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Texas</LOCATION>, supporting <PERSON>Gephardt</PERSON>, told
the rally on <DATE>Monday</DATE> that no one suffers more from the oil
industry's downturn than <LOCATION>South Texas</LOCATION> Hispanics.
   ``If you want somebody who speaks Spanish, I do a little of that
and I can interpret for <PERSON>Dick</PERSON>,'' <PERSON>Bustamante</PERSON> said, noting that
<PERSON>Gephardt</PERSON> has begun studying Spanish. <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON>Henry
Cisneros</PERSON> has stayed neutral, although his wife has endorsed <PERSON>Dukakis</PERSON>.
   Gephardt recalled he trained for the <ORGANIZATION>Missouri Air National Guard</ORGANIZATION>
at <ORGANIZATION>Lackland Air Force Base</ORGANIZATION> near here. He then attacked <PERSON>Dukakis</PERSON> for
wanting to cut the defense budget.
   ``He's going to leave us in jeopardy and vulnerable,'' <PERSON>Gephardt</PERSON>
said.
   He continued to criticize his foes for opposing an oil-import
fee.
   ``Anyone like <PERSON>Al Gore</PERSON> or <PERSON>Michael Dukakis</PERSON> who tells you that
they're for making <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> energy independent is simply trying to
deceive you in a shameful way,'' <PERSON>Gephardt</PERSON> said after touring
<ORGANIZATION>Dresser Industries</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION> plant that <PERSON>Gephardt</PERSON> said shows the
need for long-term domestic energy policy because of its nearly <PERCENT>50
percent</PERCENT> cutbacks in operation.
   Gephardt has concentrated on <PERSON>Gore</PERSON> and <PERSON>Dukakis</PERSON> in his <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>
swing. Polls indicate he and Gore are battling for third behind
<PERSON>Dukakis</PERSON> and civil rights leader <PERSON>Jesse Jackson</PERSON>. But <PERSON>Gephardt</PERSON> said
his chances for winning <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> were good.
</TEXT>
