<HEAD>Soviet Officer Visiting Oklahoma After Seeing Demonstrators In
Texas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Fixes dateline; INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs, `This
is...', to add quote from Akhromeyev, picking up 4th graf pvs,
`Saturday morning...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>'s top-ranking military
officer saw traditional Indian dancing and an old-fashioned cowboy
shoot-'em-up <DATE>Saturday</DATE> on a whirlwind visit to <LOCATION>Oklahoma</LOCATION> after
protesters in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> told his delegation to ``Go home, murderers.''
   Soviet Marshal <PERSON>Sergei F. Akhromeyev</PERSON> and his group also got to
see cattle roping, trick roping and square dancing as the state
provided the visitors with a taste of Western heritage.
   This is the first visit of the ranking Soviet military leader to
the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. The weeklong tour of several cities is designed
to give the Soviet officers the chance to see typical American life
in addition to the military aspects.
   ``The times really have been changing for the better, and are
changing for the better, because of the politically courageous
decisions by our two political leaders,'' <PERSON>Ahkromeyev</PERSON> said shortly
before the evening ended. ``We need to carry out and maintain a
stable and friendly relationship.''
   <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME>, when the Soviet delegation was at the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION> in
<LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION>, two demonstrators told <PERSON>Akhromeyev</PERSON> that he did not
belong at <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>' most famous shrine. But <PERSON>Akhromeyev</PERSON>'s visit there
was more peaceful than the greeting he received upon his arrival in
<LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION> on <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>.
   About 50 demonstrators chanted ``Go home, murderers!'' when
<PERSON>Akhromeyev</PERSON> and several other Soviet officers showed up at the
<ORGANIZATION>Institute of Texan Cultures</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``I feel it's really a crime to invite these killers here when
they are committing genocide in <LOCATION>Afghanistan</LOCATION> and terrorism around
the world,'' said <PERSON>Sayed Nasir</PERSON>, a mechanical engineer from
<LOCATION>Afghanistan</LOCATION>.
   Oklahoma Gov. <PERSON>Henry Bellmon</PERSON> was host for <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME>'s
entertainment. During the festivities, <PERSON>Akhromeyev</PERSON> was presented
with an Indian headdress, and he and several other Soviet officials
were invited to try their hand at branding some cattle. None took
up the offer.
   Ten-year-old <PERSON>Charlie Ward</PERSON> was one of a group of youngsters who
took part in a trick roping demonstration for the entourage. ``It
made me feel good,'' he said afterward. ``It's the kind of
friendship between the Soviets and Americans, getting to know
them.''
   Earlier in the day, <PERSON>Akhromeyev</PERSON> and <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Adm. <PERSON>William Crowe</PERSON>,
chairman of the <ORGANIZATION>Joint Chiefs of Staff</ORGANIZATION>, toured the <ORGANIZATION>University of
Oklahoma</ORGANIZATION> campus. Crowe is a native of <LOCATION>Oklahoma</LOCATION>.
   ``I think it's a positive thing that these two guys can
communicate on all levels,'' said an onlooker, <PERSON>Neil Kingsley</PERSON>.
``They seem to understand each other.''
</TEXT>
