<LEADPARA>  A man poured gasoline on himself and set himself ablaze Tuesday in front of
the Alamo, authorities said. The man was badly burned but survived.;    At
least two tourists made videotapes, apparently believing it was a stunt.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  I'VE SACRIFICED MY FLESH. THIS IS A HOLY
SHRINE.
'
MAN SETS SELF AFIRE AT ALAMO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "Finally some kids jumped in and got him on the ground," said one witness.;
   'Sacrificed my flesh';    One videotape that KSAT-TV aired showed the man
walking around after the fire was extinguished, shouting to dozens of tourists
at the Alamo: "I've sacrificed my flesh. This is a holy shrine.";    <PERSON>Wesley
Westbrook</PERSON>, 40, was in critical condition <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> at <ORGANIZATION>Brooke Army Medical
Center</ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON>Brooke</PERSON> spokesman Capt. <PERSON>Gaston Bathalon.</PERSON>;    <PERSON>Westbrook</PERSON> had
second-degree burns over <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of his body and third-degree burns over
another <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT>, said Fire District chief aide <PERSON>Ruben Cevallos.</PERSON>;    Gas can
in truck;    <ORGANIZATION>Cevallos</ORGANIZATION> said emergency workers heard <PERSON>Westbrook</PERSON> talking about
religion while they were treating him near the historic building, where
religious activists often gather to preach.;    <PERSON>Cevallos</PERSON> said an empty
one-gallon gasoline container was found in <LOCATION>Westbrook</LOCATION>'s truck, parked 50 yards
north of the <LOCATION>Alamo</LOCATION>. A matchbook was recovered near the truck, he said. The
truck's registration papers were from <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION>, but <PERSON>Westbrook</PERSON>'s hometown
wasn't immediately known.  </TEXT>
