<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An alleged drug kingpin and two other inmates
escaped from a privately run prison across from the police station
after one of them pulled a gun on a guard, authorities said.
   Five federal agencies plus Mexican, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and local officials
were searching today for the men who escaped <DATE>Sunday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME>. They
include <PERSON>Mario Alberto Salinas Trevino</PERSON>, who federal authorities
allege masterminded one of the largest drug-smuggling and
money-laundering rings between <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>.
   Police said the three men may be heading to <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION> and are
considered armed and dangerous. At its closest point, the border is
about 100 miles away.
   Salinas, 37, was among 25 people arrested in <DATE>March 1989</DATE> in a
drug operation dubbed ``Operation Jet Set.''
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Marshal <PERSON>Bill Jonas</PERSON> said <MONEY>$10 million</MONEY> was seized from <PERSON>Salinas</PERSON>
then, and he's suspected of having up to <MONEY>$10 million</MONEY> in drug money
stashed in a hideaway either in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> or <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>.
   Prosecutors charge that between <DATE>1983</DATE> and <DATE>1989</DATE>, a drug ring
<PERSON>Salinas</PERSON> helped run was responsible for transporting more than
46,000 pounds of marijuana and 1,900 pounds of cocaine. The ring
allegedly distributed the drugs throughout <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION>.
   The ring also is accused of laundering of more than <MONEY>$7.6
million</MONEY>, using financial institutions in <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Roma</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>San Ysidro</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, to launder narcotics profits.
   Jonas identified the other inmates as <PERSON>Charlie Edward Compton</PERSON>,
58, and <PERSON>Juan Chapa Garza</PERSON>, 44. Compton was awaiting trial on federal
charges of possession of cocaine with intent to distribute. Chapa
was charged with possession of marijuana with intent to distribute.
The charges were not related to the ``Jet Set'' probe.
   Compton and <PERSON>Salinas</PERSON> are <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> citizens, <PERSON>Jonas</PERSON> said. He wasn't
sure about <PERSON>Chapa</PERSON>'s nationality.
   The three were cellmates at the <ORGANIZATION>Central Texas Parole Violators
Facility</ORGANIZATION>, a minimum- to medium-security prison in the old <LOCATION>Bexar
County</LOCATION> jail operated by <ORGANIZATION>Wackenhut Corp.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Coral Gables</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla</LOCATION>.
   Compton summoned a guard, claiming he was ill, and pulled a
handgun on him shortly before <TIME>9 p.m.</TIME>, <PERSON>Jonas</PERSON> said.
   The three then locked up two guards in the closet and
overpowered another guard on the ground floor before seizing the
security control panels and opening a door, <PERSON>Jonas</PERSON> said. They fled
on foot.
   According to police reports, <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION> police weren't notified
of the jailbreak until nearly an hour after the three men had
escaped.
   But <ORGANIZATION>Wackenhut</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Pat Cannan</PERSON> said police were notified 15
to 20 minutes after the jail break by the guard on the ground
floor, who was tied up outside.
   ``It took him about 15 to 20 minutes to get unloose and he ran
straight across the street to the police department,'' <PERSON>Cannan</PERSON> said.
``That was the proper thing to do.''
   <PERSON>Jonas</PERSON> said he had no indication that <ORGANIZATION>Wackenhut</ORGANIZATION> had delayed the
reporting unneccessarily.
   Wackenhut officials speculate the pistol was smuggled into the
prison during Easter Day visiting hours, <PERSON>Cannan</PERSON> said. He spoke in a
telephone interview from <LOCATION>Coral Gables</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Jonas</PERSON> said the gun was
believed to be a .25-caliber.
   ``We suspect it was brought in by a visitor,'' he said. <PERSON>Cannan</PERSON>
said the prison screens visitors, but he declined to give details.
   The inmates were being held in the private facility for the <ORGANIZATION>U.S.
Marshal's Service</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Cannan</PERSON> said. The 620-capacity prison was housing
583 people <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, about 100 of them <ORGANIZATION>Marshal's Service</ORGANIZATION> prisoners,
<PERSON>Cannan</PERSON> said. The prison has 125 guards, 20 to 25 per shift, he said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Marshal's Service</ORGANIZATION> has summoned assistance from the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Drug
Enforcement Adminstration</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>FBI</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Customs Service</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Immigration and
Naturalization Service</ORGANIZATION> and Mexican customs, <PERSON>Jonas</PERSON> said. State and
local officials also were involved in the search.
</TEXT>
